  "prompt": "What is the difference between centripetal force and centrifugal force?",
  "response": "Centripetal force and centrifugal force are both concepts related to circular motion, but they describe different phenomena and they are often confused. \n\n1. **Centripetal Force**:\n   - **Definition**: Centripetal force is the force that acts on an object moving in a circular path and is directed towards the center of the circle around which the object is moving.\n   - **Nature**: It is a real force, necessary for circular motion.\n   - **Examples**: Tension in a string for a swinging object, gravitational force for planets orbiting the sun, frictional force for a car turning on a curve.\n   - **Direction**: Inward, towards the center of the circular path.\n   - **Formula**: \\( F_c = \\frac{mv^2}{r} \\) where \\( m \\) is mass, \\( v \\) is velocity, and \\( r \\) is the radius of the circular path.\n\n2. **Centrifugal Force**:\n   - **Definition**: Centrifugal force is the apparent force that an object feels when it is in a rotating reference frame, appearing to push the object away from the center of rotation.\n   - **Nature**: It is not a real force but a perceived effect due to inertia. This is technically known as a \"pseudo-force\" or \"fictitious force\".\n   - **Examples**: Feeling pushed outward when in a rotating amusement park ride, sensing that objects are pushed outward when stirring a liquid.\n   - **Direction**: Outward, away from the center of the circular path.\n   - **Context**: Only experienced in a non-inertial (accelerating) frame of reference.\n\nIn summary, centripetal force is the actual force that keeps an object in circular motion by pulling it towards the center, while centrifugal force is the perceived effect of inertia experienced as an outward force when in a rotating reference frame.",
